Package actions

Class Action

  • java.lang.Object
    • actions.Action
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable
    public class Action
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable
    Contains the keypresses and durations for a single action. Works like an uneditable Queue. Call poll() to get the keystrokes at each timestep execution. Call hasNext() to make sure there are timesteps left in this action. Call reset() to restore the duration of the action back to original.

    Note that when constructed, actions may not be changed or polled. They serve as an "immutable" backup of the action. To get a pollable version of the Action, call getCopy().

    Author:
    Matt
    See Also:
    Queue, ActionSet, Serialized Form

      • equals

        public boolean equals​(java.lang.Object other)
        Check if this action is equal to another in regards to keypresses and durations. Completely overrides default equals, so when doing ArrayList checks, this will be the only way to judge. Note that the actions do not need to have the same number of timesteps remaining to be judged as equal as long as their timestep totals and keys are the same.
        Overrides:
        equals in class java.lang.Object
        Parameters:
        other - An action to check whether it is equivalent to this action.
        Returns:
        Whether the other action is equivalent to this one.

      • getCopy

        public Action getCopy()
        Get a copy of this action. This avoid multi-threading issues.

      • isMutable

        public boolean isMutable()
        Is this a mutable copy of the original action? Important if we plan to use this as a pollable queue. If the action is not mutable, then you must get a copy with getCopy().
        Returns:
        Returns whether this action can be polled. If false, then it is the original version of the action.

      • consolidateActions

        public static java.util.List<Action> consolidateActions​(java.util.List<Action> inActions)
        Take a list of actions and combine adjacent actions which have the same keypresses. These mostly arise when doing control on a timestep-by-timestep basis. Only timestepsTotal are used. Timesteps remaining are not preserved. 0-duration actions are squashed away. An empty array input or one containing nothing but 0 length actions will produce an exception.
        Parameters:
        inActions - A list of actions which we wish to consolidate.
        Returns:
        A new list of actions which is the consolidated version of the input action list.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - When trying to consolidate a list of actions containing nothing but 0-length actions.
